column4: <content>Bosch-Bruegel. Dulle Griet. Two winged fish-like monsters in the air above the glass bell are from Bosch's Temptation of St. Antony; Styx with boat in Last Judgment: This apparently also in Dulle Griet (above the glass bell to the left) as observed by L. [Leonard] Rosoman, Bruegel's Mad Meg, Lo. [London: Cassell], 1969, p. 27; Rosoman, loc.cit. 'The harp was looked on as a symbol of greed.' [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. The harp is exactly above Dulle Griet. If this statement about the harp is correct this would confirm my interpretation. Look up Bax: Greed for Rosoman means Gula.</content>
